This paper deals with a problem in computational geometry, specifically covering the boundary of a polygon with disks, which is a classic problem in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The algorithm presented in the paper involves sorting and binary search, which are common techniques in algorithms and data structures, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) another likely sub-category. The problem also involves finding a minimum cover, which is a combinatorial optimization problem, making cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) a possible sub-category. The paper also deals with the concept of geodesic disks, which is related to the study of distance and shortest paths, making cs.GR (Graphics) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper presents an algorithm that involves some heuristics and approximation techniques, which are common in the field of artificial intelligence and optimization, making cs.SI (Artificial Intelligence and Optimization) a possible sub-category.
